{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5f03905f-7125-4da0-b907-5e496190d7b4","content":"Your project is already set up with the HotReload package. Here's how to use it:\n\n**Run tests in hot-reload mode:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis starts a watch session — when you save changes to your `.cs` files, tests automatically re-run without a full rebuild.\n\n**Your current issue:** `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` fails because `IsValidEmail` only checks for non-empty strings but doesn't validate the `@` sign. In hot-reload mode, you'd fix `IsValidEmail`, save the file, and see the test results update instantly.\n\n**Workflow:**\n1. `dotnet test --hotreload` in one terminal\n2. Edit & save code in another\n3. See results refresh automatically\n\nThis is much faster than running `dotnet test` repeatedly since it skips the full build cycle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"855f6fa5-e9a6-406f-a57e-674eb7cb3952","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a test project with HotReload already configured. They want to know how to use it to iterate on fixes. Let me explain the workflow.\n\nThe `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package enables `dotnet test --hotreload` which watches for file changes and re-runs tests automatically without a full rebuild.\n\nLet me check the current test state first, then explain the workflow.","outputTokens":309,"requestId":"A030:343F6:19E83F8:1D591FF:69FE908F"},"id":"8a2e6e96-633c-4089-8790-89ca605e16e9","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:40:42.728Z","parentId":"01773a72-fbac-46e6-ae50-87cba05a8ffc"}
